3.5 CALCULATE CHEMICAL SIMILARITIES

  • Based on all the SMILES chemical representations, in another notebook excluded from here for simplification purposes (note that the file created that contains all the required data is 0.3 GB), the Tanimoto chemical similarities based on 6 different fingerprints (FCFP4, BPF, BTD, PATH, AP, ECFP4) are calculated. The way it is calculated is based on functions provided within the GuacaMol library (https://github.com/BenevolentAI/guacamol)
  • Note that the way to calculate the similarities based on SMILES is explained below for prediction purposes
  • Also the product of all the 6 fingerprint-based Tanimoto similarities is calculated. This will be used later on for filtering using a threshold (to be explained later).
In [12]:
chem_sim = pd.read_csv(r'C:\Users\Javier\IE Students\Term 3 - Data Dynamos - Documentos\General\Social Network Analysis\drugs\Javier\final\FINAL_EDGES_SIMILARITY_vF.csv')
chem_sim['chem_sim_PROD'] = chem_sim['FCFP4_tanimoto_sim'] * chem_sim['BPF_tanimoto_sim'] * chem_sim['BTF_tanimoto_sim'] \
                         * chem_sim['PATH_tanimoto_sim'] * chem_sim['AP_tanimoto_sim'] * chem_sim['ECFP4_tanimoto_sim']
chem_sim['chem_sim_PROD'] = chem_sim['chem_sim_PROD'] / (np.max(chem_sim['chem_sim_PROD']))

chem_sim = chem_sim.drop("Unnamed: 0", axis=1)

3.4 CHEMICAL SIMILARITIES THRESHOLD

  • The idea of taking the product of different 6 chemical similarities is to penalize those that have a zero in any of the chemical similarities.
  • Not only those equal to zero, but a threshold is set, in this case equal to 0.008.
  • This threshold is user-defined, and it was put based on getting a reasonable balance between number of edges and communities afterwards. Note that if all weighted edges are left, it would be difficult to create differentiated communities, therefore, a threshold is needed.
  • After filtering with that threshold, a total of 2651 chemical similarities are left.
  • Once filtered by a combination-product of tanimoto similarities, now the edge weights will be taken as tje fCFP4-fingerprint chemical similarities.

3.5 GRAPH CONSTRUCTION

  • In this step the graph is built in python igraph.
  • After instantiating the object graph, the nodes are loaded.
  • Then the weights are loaded as type1.
  • This is to be able to build a multigraph with the interaction edges later on.
  • However, the interaction edges finally later on were queried without loading into a multigraph, as this caused some issues in igraph when calculating communities.
In [16]:
G_drugs = ig.Graph()
In [17]:
# Setting up nodes
nodes_list_chem_sim = list(nodes_smiles_df['molecule'])

G_drugs.add_vertices(nodes_list_chem_sim)
In [18]:
for _, row in chem_sim_sel.iterrows():
    # add an edge with type 1 and the weight from the 'weight' column
    G_drugs.add_edge(row['drug_name_A'], row['drug_name_B'], type=1, weight=row['FCFP4_tanimoto_sim'])

3.6 COMMUNITY DETECTION

  • Once the graph has been initialized and loaded, the Louvain community algorithm is applied in order to detect different communities based on chemical similarity.
  • Since the number of communities is large the print-out of all of them has been deactivated in this notebook, but later on a selection of the most important ones is printed out.
  • A random seed is set in order to get reproducible results run over run.
  • A visualization of the graph is performed using "graphopt" option in igraph.
  • 3 specific communities are highlighted for presentation purposes to locate them in the graph, but deactivated here for simplicity.

3.6.A LOUVAIN

In [21]:
import random
random.seed(42)

# Run community detection algorithm
communities_orig_louvain = G_drugs.community_multilevel(weights=G_drugs.es.select(type=1)['weight'], return_levels=False)

# communities_orig_louvain = communities_orig_louvain.as_clustering(2)

modularity_score_louvain = G_drugs.modularity(communities_orig_louvain.membership)

#print(communities_orig_louvain)

In [23]:
# Get community sizes
community_sizes = communities_orig_louvain.sizes()

# Sort community sizes in descending order
sorted_sizes = sorted(community_sizes, reverse=True)
#print(sorted_sizes)

# Get indices of 10 largest communities
largest_communities = [sorted_sizes[3]] + [sorted_sizes[10]] + [sorted_sizes[11]]
largest_community_indices = [i for i, size in enumerate(community_sizes) if size in largest_communities]
#print(largest_communities)

# Create a list of labels for each vertex in the graph
vertex_labels = ['' for i in range(G_drugs.vcount())]

# Set the label for the vertices in the 10 largest communities
for i in largest_community_indices:
    members = communities_orig_louvain[i]
    for j in members:
        vertex_labels[j] = '#{}'.format(i+1)

In [25]:
list_comm_louvain = []
list_comm_mols_louvain = []
list_comm_smiles_louvain = []
list_comm_size_louvain = []
for zz in communities_orig_louvain:
    list_comm_louvain.append(zz)
    list_indiv_louvain = []
    list_indiv_smiles_louvain = []
    for ww in zz:
        #print(ww)
        list_indiv_louvain.append(nodes_list_chem_sim[ww])
        list_indiv_smiles_louvain.append(nodes_smiles_df['smiles'][nodes_smiles_df['molecule']==nodes_list_chem_sim[ww]].iloc[0]) 
        
    list_comm_mols_louvain.append(list_indiv_louvain)
    list_comm_smiles_louvain.append(list_indiv_smiles_louvain)
    list_comm_size_louvain.append(len(list_indiv_louvain))
#list_comm_size_louvain

3.7 COMMUNITY CHARACTERISTICS

  • Once the communities have been identified, the characteristics of both the nodes that compose that community as well as the type of interactions those nodes of that community have with others is analyzed

NODE INFORMATION:MAIN ATC ANALYSIS¶

  • With the following code some examples of identified communities are printed out.
  • The communities that have more than 5 drugs as well as a clear ATC that represents the group (more than 50%) is printed out.
  • Note the coherent molecules inside each group, having similar names, indicating likely similar chemical structures.
  • Therefore, seems that the communities based on chemical structures similarities is working correctly!

EDGE INFORMATION: MAJOR INTERACTIONS ANALYSIS¶

  • For edge information, we have focused on analyzing and assigning the average degree for major interactions to each community.
  • After preparing the corresponding edges dataframes, the final dataframe of edges is queried in order to calculate the average degree for major interactions for the communities printed out in previous step.
  • Note that with both we have a very good descriptor of each community, with ATC and interaction information.

3.8 ATC & MAJOR INTERACTION PREDICTION TOOL

  • Finally, in this step a prediction for a new drug - molecule that is NOT contained in the previous dataset is performed.
  • The idea is to create a new node for the new molecule, calculate all the edges as chemical similarities between this new molecule and all existing ones in the dataset, and create the communities to see to which one it belongs to.
  • Then, assign the properties of the community it belongs to, to the new molecule.
  • This way we can assign the most likely ATC that will treat as well as the average degree of major interactions (and also the typical major interactions that it will have).

Steps:¶

  • Step 0: A new molecule being developed as a new drug is chosen
  • Step 1: A SMILES chemical structure representation is obtained
  • Step 2: The FCFP4 and rest of fingerprints are calculated
  • Step 3: The Tanimoto similarities are calculated
  • Step 4: The new node and calculated edges are included and communities recalculated
  • Step 5: The average community metrics of the existing drugs are calculated
  • Step 6: Those are assigned to the new molecule

Steps 0 and 1:¶

  • Below are some examples from FDA website on recently approved molecules.
  • These molecules are NOT contained in our dataset.
  • They are meant to test the chemical similarity graph.
  • One can activate or deactivate any of the below ones, but one at a time.

Steps 2 and 3:¶

  • Now the required function (TanimotoScoringFunction) is imported from guacamol python library.
  • The Tanimoto similarities using 6 different fingerprints (BPF, BTF, PATH, AP, ECFP4, FCFP4) is calculated for each pairwise combination of the new molecule and the ones already in the dataset.
  • As before, a threshold over the product of the 6 similarities is applied (same thershold as before).
  • Finally, this new edges are merged (pd.concat) with the previous edges in order to rebuild a new graph.

import guacamol
from guacamol.common_scoring_functions import TanimotoScoringFunction

import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

final_df5 = new_chem_sim.copy()

final_df5['BPF_tanimoto_sim'] = 0.0
listcount = np.linspace(0,900000,241)
count=0
for zz in range(final_df5.shape[0]):
    mol1 = final_df5['smiles_A'][zz]
    mol2 = final_df5['smiles_B'][zz]
    tanimoto_func = TanimotoScoringFunction(target=mol1, fp_type='BPF')
    final_df5['BPF_tanimoto_sim'][zz] = tanimoto_func.score(mol2)
    count = count +1
    if float(count) in listcount: print(count)
        
final_df5['BTF_tanimoto_sim'] = 0.0

  • Now the new graph is built in the same way as above, just with more edges (more chemical similarities)
  • After building it, the Louvain community detection algorithm is run again.
  • If the new node is assigned to a community with at least 1 previous node from the dataset, it will be possible to make a prediction for the new molecule regarding ATC and major interactions degree, based on the average of the community it belongs to.

SUMMARY DESCRIPTION & PREDICTION:¶

  • It has been shown in this notebook the feasibility of building a chemical similarity network in order to:

    A. Describe the communities within the known dataset in terms of ATCs and major interactions avg degree. B. Predict, based on to which community the new molecule belongs to, the most likely ATC that will treat as well as the major interactions degree that will have. The graph also allows to go deeper and get to individual interactions as needed.
